## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Timeout Enforcement Pattern

### Why it breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`). The entire preemptive-abort model is removed.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run schedules work on the thread pool (no manual Thread needed)
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

            // WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the token fires
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Async overload (preferred in modern .NET)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Caller migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeExpensiveResult(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must accept and check the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    token =>
    {
        // Check cancellation at regular checkpoints
        foreach (var item in items)
        {
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            Process(item);
        }
        return ComputeResult();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls for This Code

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the token doesn't inject an exception mid-execution. If `work` never checks `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`, it runs to completion regardless of timeout. |
| **Signature change is required** | `Func<T>` → `Func<CancellationToken, T>`. Every call site must be updated to accept and check the token. This is the biggest migration cost. |
| **Don't forget `using`** | The old code leaked the `Thread`. `CancellationTokenSource` owns internal timers — always dispose it. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort` has no equivalent** | The old catch block swallowed the abort. In cooperative cancellation, you simply don't call `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` if you want to continue. |
| **Blocking I/O won't cancel** | If `work` calls `Thread.Sleep` or synchronous `socket.Read`, the token won't interrupt it. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O overloads. |

### What changed and why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` | `Task.Run(..., token)` | Thread pool is more efficient; token wires up cancellation |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `.WaitAsync(cts.Token)` | Cancellation-aware waiting (.NET 6+ API) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.CancelAfter(timeout)` via constructor | Cooperative signal replaces forced termination |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No abort to reset — cancellation is voluntary |
